<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-31T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-31T09:00:00-05:00" n="526" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d526">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5331/136: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Portugal</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lisbon</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-31T15:00:00+01:00">March 31, 1935—3
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 31—1:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>4. Department’s telegram March 30, 6 p.m. In other cases, notably
                                Germany and Japan, Portugal has conceded abolition of flag
                                discrimination on a temporary basis, pending negotiations. I believe
                                that firm insistence on such a minimum would add to American
                                prestige here.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Caldwell</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>